# DistrictSync pinned SSH host keys (standard OpenSSH known_hosts format).
#
# When this file contains an entry for an SFTP server, DistrictSync verifies the
# server's identity against it on every connection and REFUSES to deliver if the
# offered key does not match (protection against man-in-the-middle attacks).
# Servers with NO entry here are still accepted, with a warning in the log —
# pinning only ever tightens security, it never blocks delivery before keys exist.
#
# Keys below were scanned 2026-07-20. To ROTATE them, run this from any machine that can reach
# the servers on port 22, then paste the output lines below (one per line):
#
#   ssh-keyscan -t ed25519,ecdsa,rsa sftp.ca.spacesedu.com sftp.app.spacesedu.com sftp.myblueprint.ca
#
# Each entry line looks like:  <hostname> <key-type> <base64-public-key>
#
# NON-STANDARD PORT: if delivery uses any port other than 22, the lookup name is
# "[hostname]:port" — scan with `ssh-keyscan -p PORT -t ed25519,ecdsa,rsa <host>`
# (its output already uses the bracketed form) and paste that line as-is. A
# plain-hostname entry does NOT pin a non-22 connection.
#
# No-release hotfix path: a known_hosts file placed in the DistrictSync app-data
# folder (Windows: %LOCALAPPDATA%\DistrictSync\known_hosts) takes precedence over
# this bundled file, so keys can be added or rotated on a district server without
# shipping a new build.
